'united-arab-emirates': {
  lifeEconomics: "Zero income tax is the headline — and it is real. A $6,000/month salary in Dubai is $6,000 in your pocket. But living costs are high: a 1-bed in Dubai Marina runs AED 6,000-10,000/month ($1,600-2,700), school fees for one child can exceed $15,000/year, and brunch culture, dining, and entertainment add up fast. Abu Dhabi is slightly cheaper. The savings potential is genuinely enormous if you are disciplined; many expats save 40-60% of their income.",
  housingLivingReality: "Modern, air-conditioned, and well-maintained — UAE apartments are built for comfort. Landlords traditionally demand 1-4 cheques for the full year's rent upfront (this is changing but still common). EJARI registration in Dubai is mandatory for your tenancy contract. Furnished apartments are widely available for short-term stays. Areas like JBR, Downtown, and Marina are expat-heavy and walkable; outer areas like JVC and Dubailand are cheaper but car-dependent. Bayut and Property Finder are the main platforms.",
  workIncomeReality: "Employer-sponsored visas are the standard path — your company sponsors your residence permit, and losing your job means a 30-day grace period to find a new sponsor or leave. This power dynamic is real and affects negotiations. Work hours are long (9-10 hour days are common), and the culture is results-driven and hierarchical. Dubai's free zones (DMCC, DIFC, JAFZA) enable freelancers and entrepreneurs to sponsor themselves. The Golden Visa (10-year residency) has loosened the employer dependency for high earners and investors.",
  taxesSocialSystem: "No personal income tax, no capital gains tax, no wealth tax. A 5% VAT on goods and services is the main levy. Corporate tax (9% above AED 375,000 profit) was introduced in 2023. There is no public welfare system for expats — no unemployment benefits, no state pension. Your employer must provide health insurance and an end-of-service gratuity (roughly 21 days' salary per year). Everything else is your responsibility.",
  healthcareReality: "Employer-provided health insurance is mandatory in Dubai and Abu Dhabi, and the quality of private healthcare is excellent. Cleveland Clinic Abu Dhabi, Mediclinic, and Aster are top-tier. Wait times are short, facilities are modern, and most doctors speak English. Out-of-pocket costs depend entirely on your insurance plan — some are comprehensive, others cover only basics. Dental and vision are often excluded. Without insurance, a specialist visit costs AED 300-800 ($80-220).",
  transportationMobility: "Dubai is a car city — distances are vast, summer heat makes walking brutal, and urban design assumes you drive. Renting a car costs AED 1,500-3,000/month. The Dubai Metro covers major corridors (Red and Green lines) and is clean and cheap but limited in reach. Taxis and Careem/Uber are widely used. Abu Dhabi is even more car-dependent. Parking in popular areas is a constant headache. Salik (road tolls) in Dubai add AED 4 per gate crossing.",
  internationalConnectivity: "Dubai International (DXB) and the new Al Maktoum International are among the world's busiest airports. Emirates, Etihad (Abu Dhabi), and flydubai offer direct flights to virtually everywhere — 6 hours to London, 3 hours to Mumbai, 8 hours to most of Asia. The UAE's geographic position between Europe, Asia, and Africa is a genuine superpower. Weekend trips to Oman, Bahrain, or the Maldives are routine.",
  climateSeasons: "Summer (June-September) is genuinely punishing: 40-50°C with suffocating humidity. Outdoor activity is impossible during daylight hours. October-April is pleasant (20-30°C) and the real 'living season' — outdoor dining, beach days, and desert camping. The transition is abrupt. Most social and cultural life migrates indoors during summer. Air conditioning is not optional; it runs 24/7 and is factored into rent.",
  whoThisCountryIsFor: "For high earners who want to maximize savings, enjoy modern infrastructure, and do not mind a transient social scene. The UAE rewards financial ambition and professional hustle — it is less suited for those seeking deep community roots or a low-key lifestyle.",
  travelExploration: "Desert safaris, Oman road trips, and Abu Dhabi's Louvre and mangroves for weekends. Ski Dubai exists (yes, indoor skiing in the desert). The Maldives, Sri Lanka, and Jordan are popular short-haul escapes. Dubai's restaurant and nightlife scene is world-class but expensive. Friday brunch is a cultural institution — budget AED 300-500 per person."
},
